When we moved from NJ to Florida 20 years ago was the last time we traveled
with cats!  Several.  I think the answer is if it is a long enough trip they
will get over howling!  We shipped our horses with a commercial carrier so
they could all come at once, so when we pulled our trailer down we brought
most of the cats.  The trailer had a dressing room, and we had cages in
there.  They were pretty loud at first, but in a couple of hours they
settled down--by the 2 1/2 days it took to get here they were seasoned
travelers.

We had left one cat that we thought we had a home for, and the people never
came to get him.  I had flown back to NJ to close on that property and bring
our other car down, so I had the cat to bring.  I started out with him in a
carrier, and he was unhappy.  I finally let him loose in the car and he
curled up on my lap and that is where he spent the whole trip.  The only
problem was that my Doberman, who was also traveling with me, did not see
why Puff could sit on my lap while I was driving, and she could not.

But, I really do think if you had the opportunity to take the cat for a very
long ride she would get used to it, but if she didn't quiet down it would be
misery for both of you.  The &quot;long ride theory&quot; works quite well with dogs.

Barb C.

